               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18490129-name-735" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18490129-name-735" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490129-name-735" type="surname" value="HOLDEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490129-name-735" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH HOLDEN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, K</hi> 427). On 16th Jan. I stopped the prisoner in Bow-road, at night, with this copper and pipe on his shoulder, wrapped up—I asked where he got it—he said he found it by the side of the road—I found a shirt at the bottom of the copper, with three pieces of pipe in the sleeve—he said he took his shirt off, and wrapped the lead in it; that it was a very bad job, and could not be helped; that he was in the expectation of making a good night's work, and if he had been on the other side of the road it would have been all right.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18490129-name-736" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18490129-name-736" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490129-name-736" type="surname" value="BRAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490129-name-736" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD BRAND</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at Ilford. This copper and lead are mine—these were fixed to the brick-work of my house—I missed them on 17th Jan.—a square of glass was broken, and the window had been opened—the pipe matches with what is left.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I found it in the road.</p>
